This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for compile-time evaluation.

## Core concept

Constant folding evaluates expressions during compilation when the language requires a stable result.

## Beanstalk boundary

AST owns semantic checking and folding for:

- ordinary constants
- resolved source build inputs
- const records
- const templates
- compile-time page fragments

Header syntax and Stage 3 establish local declaration order before folding.

Exported folded values cross module boundaries as owned backend-neutral facts. Consumers do not reparse or refold provider templates.

Compile-time and runtime numeric, cast and formatting behaviour must agree.

`config.bst` bootstrap and `@project` creation are build-system concerns. They are not defined on this page.

## Rewrite focus

Explain constant propagation, deterministic evaluation, const records, why runtime values cannot leak into constants and why duplicate evaluators drift.

Canonical details live in both architecture authorities.
